In our books the only transactions that add to current liabilities are those “Purchase” entries that have not yet been paid (that is, they are “Unpaid” and they use a “non‐cash” payment method such as “Account Payable”). (Other transactions – for example deposits with an “Initial” label, expenses, depreciation, or “Interest Receivables” – are not part of the current liabilities.)

Thus the ending (final) total for our current liabilities is 5,015,020.0.

Step 3. Determining the “initial” current liabilities value:
In our set the “Initial20231231001” transactions are used to record the opening balances (cash, bank, fixed assets). They do not include any liability entry. So the liabilities on the opening balance sheet are nil – i.e. 0.00.

So our answer is:

 Total Current Liabilities Initial Value = 0.00  
 Total Current Liabilities End Value   = 5,015,020.00
